{"title_page": "C. Mark Jordan", "text_new": "{{For|other people with this name|Mark Jordan (disambiguation){{!}}Mark Jordan}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Mark C. Jordan\n| image =\n| alt = Mark Jordan sitting on a red [[Miata]].\n| residence = California, U.S.\n| occupation = Automotive Designer\n| employer = Mazda North American Operations\n| known_for = Design of the first generation Mazda MX-5 Miata\n| father = [[Chuck Jordan (automobile designer)|Chuck Jordan]]\n}}\n'''C. Mark Jordan''' is an automotive designer known for his work with [[General Motors]]'s [[Adam Opel AG|Opel]] division and [[Mazda North American Operations|Mazda North America]], including his part in the genesis of the first generation [[Mazda MX-5#Design genesis|Mazda MX-5 Miata]], a car that ultimately became the best-selling two-seat convertible sports car in history.<ref name=\"Guinness2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mazda.com/publicity/release/2011/201102/110204a.html |title=900,000th Mazda MX-5 to Set New Guinness World Record |publisher=Mazda.com |date=2011-02-04 |accessdate=2012-10-07}}</ref>\n\n==Background and career==\nJordan is widely known for collaborating on the design of the first generation (1989) [[Mazda MX-5#Design genesis|Mazda MX-5 Miata]], with [[Bob Hall (American motoring journalist)|Bob Hall]] and [[Tom Matano]].<ref>{{cite book\n | last = Yamaguchi\n | first = Jack K.\n | author-link =\n | last2 = Thompson\n | first2 = Jonathan\n | title = Miata Mazda MX-\n | publisher = St. Martin's Press\n | series =\n | volume =\n | edition = First\n | date = 1989\n | location = New York\n | pages = 18 and on\n | language =\n | url =\n | doi =\n | id =\n | isbn = 9780312031589\n | mr =\n | zbl =\n | jfm = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/30/style/style-makers-mark-jordan-sports-car-stylist.html|title=STYLE MAKERS; Mark Jordan: Sports Car Stylist|last=Levin|first=Doron P.|date=1989-07-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-03-14|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Hall hired Jordan to join the newly formed Mazda design studio in Southern California, where they collaborated on the parameters of the initial image, proportion and visualization of what would become Miata, a \"light-weight sports\" concept.\" \n\nThe son of noted former [[General Motors|GM]] vice president of design [[Chuck Jordan (automobile designer)|Chuck Jordan]],<ref>{{Citation\n | last = Eisenstein\n | first = Paul A.\n | author-link =\n | last2 =\n | first2 =\n | author2-link =\n | title = Designer Genes For Cars\n | newspaper = Chicago Tribune\n | pages =\n | year =\n | date = March 4, 1990\n | url =\n | archive-url =\n | archive-date =\n  }}</ref> Jordan attended [[Art Center College of Design]] (1974-1978) and worked for [[Adam Opel AG]] (1978-1982), before working with [[Mazda North American Operations]] in various roles (1982-2009).<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Braun\n | first = Stephen\n | author-link =\n | title = Drivers Studied for Future Trends : Southern California--It's the Auto Industry's Lab\n | journal = Los Angeles Times\n | volume =\n | issue =\n | pages =\n | publisher =\n | location =\n | date = 1989-10-02\n | language =\n | url = http://articles.latimes.com/1989-10-02/news/mn-393_1_southern-california-version\n | jstor =\n | issn =\n | doi =\n | id =\n | mr =\n | zbl =\n | jfm =\n | access-date = June 26, 2016 }}</ref>  He directs and manages the ''Charles M. Jordan Scholarship Fund,'' an endowment fund in honor of his late father, with the [[College for Creative Studies]] in Detroit. \n\nJordan consulted with his high school friend, [[Jeff Teague (automotive designer)|Jeff Teague]] (1956-2016) to form a design company ''JTDNA,''<ref name=\"jtdna\">{{cite web\n |title        = Auto Designer Jeff Teague, 59, Has Died\n |publisher    = 56Packardman\n |author       = \n |date         = September 8, 2016\n |url          = https://56packardman.com/2016/08/09/gear-head-tuesday-auto-designer-jeff-teague-59-has-died/}}</ref> before founding own firm, CMJ Design Consulting.\n\n==See also==\n* {{cite web\n | url = https://www.linkedin.com/in/c-mark-jordan-4a0a937\n | title = C. Mark Jordan\n | last =\n | first =\n | date =\n | website =\n | publisher =\n | access-date = June 26, 2016\n | quote = }}\n* [[Tom Matano]] (Chief of Design for Mazda North American Operations)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[File:MAZDA MIATA MX-5 U9 dutch licence registration XB-DT-95.JPG|thumbnail|left|Mazda Miata MX-5]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jordan, C. Mark}}\n[[Category:American automobile designers]]\n[[Category:General Motors designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other people with this name|Mark Jordan (disambiguation){{!}}Mark Jordan}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Mark C. Jordan\n| image =\n| alt = Mark Jordan sitting on a red [[Miata]].\n| residence = California, U.S.\n| occupation = Automotive Designer\n| employer = Mazda North American Operations\n| known_for = Design of the first generation Mazda MX-5 Miata\n| father = [[Chuck Jordan (automobile designer)|Chuck Jordan]]\n}}\n'''C. Mark Jordan''' is an automotive designer known for his work with [[General Motors]]'s [[Adam Opel AG|Opel]] division and [[Mazda North American Operations|Mazda North America]], including his part in the genesis of the first generation [[Mazda MX-5#Design genesis|Mazda MX-5 Miata]], a car that ultimately became the best-selling two-seat convertible sports car in history.<ref name=\"Guinness2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mazda.com/publicity/release/2011/201102/110204a.html |title=900,000th Mazda MX-5 to Set New Guinness World Record |publisher=Mazda.com |date=2011-02-04 |accessdate=2012-10-07}}</ref>\n\n==Background and career==\nJordan is widely known for collaborating on the design of the first generation (1989) [[Mazda MX-5#Design genesis|Mazda MX-5 Miata]], with [[Bob Hall (American motoring journalist)|Bob Hall]] and [[Tom Matano]].<ref>{{c